Text.Value: That's because you still have hope. But when he becomes your last hope, remember this.
He spoke of a cure. We have to at least hear him out.
Take a single step towards him, and he'll dog you the whole journey.
So you say.
With the right teacher, yes. What are your thoughts on the devil, Wyll?
He'll require of you only what you're least ready to part with.
I didn't, and I couldn't. My soul was a necessary price to pay for... hrm-hrh...

EditorData.NodeContext: Wyll makes a few hoarse sounds at the end, as if he's losing his voice.

Text.Value: Trust me: he'll take what you're least ready to part with.
Get to the point.
You might think you'd give up anything for a cure.
Refuse him, no matter how tempting the offer, no matter how delicious the feast he lays out for you. The cost will be too great.
Don't worry. I have no interest in a devil's deal.
And given the same circumstance, I'd do it again. My soul was a necessary price to pay for... hrm-hrh...

EditorData.NodeContext: Wyll makes a few hoarse sounds at the end, as if he's losing his voice.

Text.Value: But the devil won't take just anything. He'll take everything.
That's because you still have hope. But when he becomes your last hope, remember this.
He brings to mind a story. 'The Devil with the Silver Tongue.'
Ahem. I'm afraid I can't say more about it. But I can say this:
Spare me the parables - I've no intention of bargaining with the likes of him.
We can learn a lot from fairy tales, don't you think?
An old fairy tale my father read to me. The kind with a hero, a villain, and a moral.
You mean Raphael? We should at least consider his offer, given our circumstances.
The farmer's dearest fruit, naturally, was no apple nor peach, but his beloved daughter.
And then require more still.
A devil wouldn't bargain if he thought there was no chance of success, Lae'zel.
Ahem. You know I can't say more. But I can say this:

EditorData.logicalname: Wyll has said he can't talk of the pact

Text.Value: Refuse him like you refused Mizora? Only, you didn't, did you?
No cost is too great, if it rids me of this infection.
And then take more still.
The devil made an empty promise. Our only hope lies with my people.

EditorData.logicalname: Lae'zel, hasn't been to creche yet

Text.Value: Do not trust Raphael. Is that plain enough?
A farmer made a deal with a devil, so the story goes: in exchange for the farmer's dearest fruit, the devil granted him a bottomless coinpurse.
Interesting, coming from someone who's already been ensnared by a devil.
I had but one road I could travel. For now, you have a dozen, a hundred, a thousand even to choose from. A road that leads to a devil is the very last one you should follow.
